Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the companys future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

Data Analysis Process

1) ASK

Guiding Questions
  • How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?
  • Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?
  • How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?
Consider key stakeholders
  • Lily Moreno: The director of marketing and your manager. Moreno is responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-share program. These may include email, social media, and other channels.
  • Cyclistic executive team: The notoriously detail-oriented executive team will decide whether to approve the recommended marketing program.
Identify the Business Task

Both the Director of Marketing and finance analysts have concluded that annual members are more profitable in previous analysis. Therefore, the business task is to present marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members.

2) PREPARE

Download data and store it appropriately.
  • Bike Share data was retrieved from the Kaggle Cyclistic Bike Share dataset. 12 CSV files were downloaded and saved locally prior to importing the files into RStudio.
  • Chicago weather dataset is from the National Centers for Environmental Information. The dataset was filtered to April 2021 - March 2022 and downloaded as a CSV file.
Identify how its organized.
  • Bike Share: 12 months (April 2021 - March 2022) of Cyclistic Bike Share data is organized into 12 separate CSV (comma separated values) files. There are 15 columns per CSV with varying data types.
  • Weather: A CSV file of the weather in Chicago from April 2021 - March 2022.
Verify the datas credibility.
Bike Share Data
  • The data is slightly outdated as the last dataset was collected 8 months ago.
  • Due to COVID-19 lockdowns and provisions, the data may not be an accurate representation of how different members use the bike share service.
  • The provided data has been made available by Motivate International Inc. under this license.
  • This is a public dataset that respects data-privacy by removing riders personally identifiable information.
Weather Data
  • Dataset includes data from 405 different stations within the city of Chicago and the period of this record is 100% coverage.
  • The dataset is provided by a government entity for public use.
  • The National Climatic Data Center offers the data for free and ensures that the content is available and accessible to all.

Aggregate your data so its useful and accessible.
  1. Aggregated the following data and formatted it into a data frame:
  • Average ride_length by rider type.
  • Median ride_length by rider type.
  • Maximum ride_length by rider type.
  • Minimum ride_length by rider type.
  • Average ride_length per day of the week by rider type.
agg_total_trip <- data.frame(
  "mean" =
    c(aggregate(total_trip_data$ride_length ~ 
                  total_trip_data$member_casual, FUN = mean)),
  "median" = 
    c(aggregate(total_trip_data$ride_length ~ 
                  total_trip_data$member_casual, FUN = median)),
  "max" =
    c(aggregate(total_trip_data$ride_length ~ 
                  total_trip_data$member_casual, FUN = max)),
  "min" = 
    c(aggregate(total_trip_data$ride_length ~ 
                  total_trip_data$member_casual, FUN = min)),
  "avg ride time per day" =
    c(aggregate(total_trip_data$ride_length ~ 
                  total_trip_data$member_casual 
                + total_trip_data$day_of_week, FUN = mean))
)
  1. Transposed aggregated data for easier readability

agg_total_trip <- data.frame (t(agg_total_trip))
  1. Prior to exporting the cleaned and transformed dataset, a quick visualization was created in R.
#number of rides by rider type
total_trip_data %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(day_of_week, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(member_casual, weekday) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()
            ,average_duration = mean(ride_length)) %>% 
  arrange(member_casual, weekday)  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = weekday, y = number_of_rides, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") + 
  labs(title = "Number of Rides by Rider Type", x = "Weekday", 
       y = "Number of Rides", fill = "Rider Type")

#average duration
total_trip_data %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(day_of_week, label = TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(member_casual, weekday) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()
            ,average_duration = mean(ride_length)) %>% 
  arrange(member_casual, weekday)  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = weekday, y = average_duration, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") + 
  labs(title = "Average Ride Length by Rider Type", x = "Weekday", 
       y = "Ride Length", fill = "Rider Type")

4 & 5) ANALYZE and SHARE

  1. Dataset was exported to a CSV for use in Tableau.
write.csv(total_trip_data,"C:\\Users\\...total_trip_data.csv", row.names = FALSE)
Identify trends and relationships.
Ridership:

Members had more trips than casual riders.

Daily Ridership:

Members had more rides during the week than casual riders, but casual riders had more rides during the weekend. This indicates that members use the service to commute to and from work while casual riders use this for leisure purposes.

Average Ride Length:

On average, casual riders trips were approximately 10 minutes longer than member trips.

Average Ride Length Per Weekday:

Casual riders always had longer trips per day than members. This did not change on the weekends.

Monthly Ridership:

Generally, members had more rides per month than casual riders. The increase in total trips during the summer months can be attributed to warmer temperatures.

Bike Type:

Classic bikes were used more often by both members and casual riders.

Ridership Vs. Temperature:

There appears to be a positive correlation between the number of rides and the average temperature for that day. A power regression shows that casual riders tend to ride more when the temperature is warmer.

Trip Start Time:

The two graphs compare the number of trips by rider type during the week on the weekend. The graph shows that both rider types start their trips at similar times on the weekend, but that members start their trips mostly at 8AM and 5PM on the weekdays. This indicates that members use the bike share service to commute to and from work.

6) ACT

Conclusion
The following conclusions can be deduced from the analysis:
  • Members use the bike share service 17% more than casual riders.
  • Members use the bike share service to commute to and from work.
  • Casual riders ride their bikes for approximately 10 minutes longer than members on average.
  • There are more trips during the summer months, peaking in July.
  • As the temperature gets warmer, the number of trips increase. More so for the casual riders than the members.
Next Steps
My recommendations to the stakeholders:
  • Offer reduced membership pricing in the winter months as there are less riders during that time.
  • Offer a membership plan for 6 months instead of an annual membership. If most riders only use the service when it is warmer out, this may be an appealing subscription.
  • Offer a membership service that is based on ride length or total minutes traveled. This may entice casual riders as they tend to have longer ride lengths on average.
  • Launch social media ads for subscriptions in May as this is when people begin utilizing the bike share service.
Additional Data
Requests for additional data:
  • The total number of electric and classic bike types available. This would show what type was preferred by the riders. The current data does not show how many are available.
  • Membership IDs would show how often the same rider uses the service.
  • Membership IDs would show us how often the same rider travels the same path.
